obo:GO_0098978  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_2977  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.5: \"CPG2 and EndoB2 Co-localize and Recruit Components of the Endocytic Machinery to F-Actin\"\n- \"Triton X-100 extracted neurons were infected with lentivirus expressing a control construct or the CPG2 knockdown construct [7, 8]. The intensity of clathrin heavy chain immunofluorescence in dendritic spines was significantly reduced when CPG2 was knocked down as compared to control (Figures 5C, left, and 5D).\"\n- \"Similar to the effect of knocking down CPG2, knockdown of EndoB2 using hp62 significantly reduced clathrin heavy chain association with the spine cytoskeleton after Triton X-100 extraction (Figures 5C, right, and 5D). \"\n\nFig.6: \"EndoB2 Is Required for Activity-Dependent, but Not Constitutive, Internalization of AMPA- and NMDA-Type Glutamate Receptors\"\n- \"Constitutive internalization of AMPA- and NMDA-type glutamate receptors seemed unaffected by EndoB2 KD (Figures 6A and 6B).\"\n- \"We found a similar result, an almost 3-fold increase in GluA1 internalization in response to picrotoxin (Figure S2). Surprisingly, EndoB2 knockdown resulted in a significant decrease in activity-dependent internalization not only of GluA1 glutamate receptor subunits but also of GluA2 and GluN1 subunits (Figures 6C and 6D).\". Experimental description: - \"Cortical or hippocampal neurons were prepared from E18 Sprague Dawley rat embryos...\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2018-03-21" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_2977" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

